==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purlieu
<hw>Pur"lieu</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Corrupted (by
influence of <ets>lieu</ets> place) fr. OF. <ets>pural⟦eacute⟧e</ets>,
<ets>poral⟦eacute⟧e</ets> (equiv. to LL. <ets>perambulatio</ets> a
survey of boundaries, originally, a going through); <ets>por</ets> (L.
<ets>pro</ets>, confused, however, with L. <ets>per</ets> through) +
<ets>al⟦eacute⟧e</ets>. See <er>Pro-</er>, and <er>Alley</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>pourlieu</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Originally, the ground near a royal forest, which, having been
unlawfully added to the forest, was afterwards severed from it, and
disafforested so as to remit to the former owners their
rights.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then as a tiger, who by chance hath spied⟦br⟧
In some <qex>purlieu</qex> two gentle fawns at play.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, the outer portion of any place; an adjacent
district; environs; neighborhood.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>purlieus</xex>
of St. James.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>brokers had been incessantly plying for custom in the
<qex>purlieus</qex> of the court.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purline</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Purlin</ent>⟦br⟧
